<DOC><DOCNO> AP890424-0141 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-24-89 2022EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-FBI-CrimeStatistics     04-24 0441</FIRST><SECOND>AM-FBI-Crime Statistics,410</SECOND><HEAD>Violent Crime Up 5 Percent</HEAD><BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The number of violent crimes rose 5 percentlast year, the FBI said Monday, with aggravated assaults up 7percent.   The FBI's preliminary Uniform Crime Report for 1988 showedoverall that reported crimes rose 3 percent from 1987 to 1988.   Murders increased 3 percent and robberies were up 4 percent from1987, according to the statistics released Sunday. Rapes went up 1percent and motor vehicle thefts increased 11 percent.   Despite the general rise in killings, the number of murdersdeclined in three of the nation's largest cities.   Homicides reported to police dropped 8.8 percent in Los Angeles,4.4 percent in Chicago and 8.3 percent in Detroit.   Murders rose 64 percent in Washington, where authorities areblaming the dramatic increase in killings on warring drug dealers.   The Bush administration has detailed extra FBI and DrugEnforcement Administration agents to the nation's capital to helplocal police fight the drug-spawned crime wave.   Murders increased 36 percent in Houston, 27.8 percent inIndianapolis; 27 percent in Jacksonville, Fla.; 21.6 percent inMemphis, Tenn.; 13.3 percent in New York City, and 12.9 percent inDallas, the report said.   Murders were up 9.7 percent in Philadelphia and 4.8 percent inAtlanta.   Pittsburgh recorded a 51 percent decline in murders reported topolice.   A 3 percent rise in crime last year followed a 2 percentincrease between 1986 and 1987 and a 6 percent jump between 1985and 1986, the report said.   The crime index records the number of selected crimes reportedto state and local police agencies. The FBI also tallies the numberof burglaries, larcenies, motor vehicle thefts and arsons reportedto authorities.   Final tabulations for 1988 are expected to be released thissummer, the FBI said.   The index showed reported crimes increased 4 percent in theNortheast and the South and 3 percent in the West. There was nochange in the Midwest crime index, the bureau said.   By region, murders were up 11 percent in the Northeast, 4percent in the South and 1 percent in the West.   There was a 3 percent decline in the number of murders in theMidwest.   Small cities showed a 7 percent jump in violent crime, includingan 8 percent increase in rapes and a 6 percent increase inaggravated assault. Homicides, however, dropped 7 percent insmaller cities, the report said.   Cities with populations over 50,000 reported a 5 percent hike inviolent crime and a 6 percent increase in murders.   Arson increased 1 percent. A 3 percent incease in larger citieswas offset by declines elsewhere.</TEXT></DOC>